r = 2000\n|isbn = 978-1-57181-911-6\n}}\n* Viviane Li\u00e8vre, Jean-Yves Loude, Kalash Solstice: Winter Feasts of the Kalash of North Pakistan, Lok Virsa (1988)\n*{{cite book|author1=Ali, Shaheen Sardar |author2=Rehman, Javaid|year=2001|title=Indigenous Peoples and Ethnic Minorities of Pakistan: Constitutional and Legal Perspectives|publisher=Curzon|isbn=9780700711598|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HNyJS9YfbyoC}}\n* Paolo Graziosi, ''The Wooden Statue of Dezalik, a Kalash Divinity, Chitral, Pakistan'', Man (1961).\n* Maraini Fosco, ''Gli ultimi pagani'', Bur, Milano, 2001.\n* M. Witzel, The \u1e5agvedic Religious System and its Central Asian and Hindukush Antecedents. In: A. Griffiths & J.E.M. Houben (eds.). The Vedas: Texts, Language and Ritual. Groningen: Forsten 2004: 581\u2013636.\n* Mytte Fentz, The Kalasha. Mountain People of the Hindu Kush. Rhodos Publishers, Copenhagen 2010. {{ISBN|9788772459745}}.\n*[https://www.academia.edu/5800056 Religion as a Space for Kalash Identity: A Case Study of Village Bumburetin Kalash Valley, District Chitral], Dr. Anwaar Mohyuddin\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kalash people}}\n* [http://www.indigenouspeople.net/Pakistan.pdf IUCN, the International Union for Conservation of Nature, Kalash Protection and conservation of an endangered Minority in the Hindu Kush]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13469826 BBC article on Kalash women]\n*[http://pu.edu.pk/images/journal/szic/pdf_files/2-%20Zaheer%20Bahram%20MUSLIM%20IMPACT%20ON_june15.pdf Muslim Impact on Religion and Culture of the Kalash] Zaheer-ud-Din in Al-Adwa 43:30 (2015)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131109234711/http://kalashaheritage.org/ Kalasha Heritage] A website used by the Kalasha people to promote, conserve and protect the Kalasha tangible and intangible heritage\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151105042749/http://hgm2002.hgu.mrc.ac.uk/Abstracts/Publish/WorkshopPosters/WorkshopPoster11/hgm0533.htm Investigation of the Greek ancestry of northern Pakistani ethnic groups using Y chromosomal DNA variation]\n* [https://elinepa.org/en/the-kalash-people-in-northern-pakistan/ The Kalash People in Northern Pakistan] by Dimitra Stasinopoulou, ELINEPA, 2019\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Pakistan}}\n{{Religion in Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalash People}}\n[[Category:Kalash people| ]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Hinduism in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of South Asia]]\n[[Category:Dardic peoples]]\n[[Category:Chitral District]]\n[[Category:Indo-Aryan peoples]]\n", "name_user": "Vassiliades", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalash_people"}
{"title_page": "Unbirthday", "text_new": "[[Image:Humpty Dumpty Tenniel.jpg|thumb|right|Humpty Dumpty wearing the cravat he received as an unbirthday present from the White King and Queen. From ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'',  illustration by [[John Tenniel]].]]\n<span lang=\"Ar\">An</span> '''unbirthday''' (originally written '''un-birthday''') is an event that is typically celebrated on any or all of the 364 (365 on leap years) days in which it is not a person's [[birthday]]. It is a [[neologism]] coined by [[Lewis Carroll]] in his 1871 novel ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'',<ref>[[Lewis Carroll]] (1871). ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]''. [[s:Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There/Chapter VI|Chapter VI, \"Humpty Dumpty\"]], written as \"un-birthday\".</ref><ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' [https://archive.org/download/oedxaarch/oedxaarch.pdf vol.&nbsp;10/1] (1926). p.&nbsp;U63 (p.&nbsp;645 of the electronic version).</ref> giving rise to \"The Unbirthday Song\" in the 1951 animated feature film ''[[Alice in Wonderland (1951 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]''.<ref>\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RdsZT7WKjW8 A Very Merry Unbirthday to You]\". Retrieved on 20 September 2008.<!-- The video is an obvious violation of copyright, but could be used here under the doctrine of fair use--></ref>\n\nOne's unbirthday should not be confused with one's [[half-birthday]], which only occurs once a year.\n\nIn ''Through the Looking-Glass'', [[Humpty Dumpty]] is wearing a [[cravat]] (which [[Alice (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Alice]] at first mistakes for a [[belt (clothing)|belt]]) which he says was given to him as an \"un-birthday present\" by the [[White King (Through the Looking-Glass)|White King]] and [[White Queen (Through the Looking-Glass)|Queen]]. He then has Alice calculate the number of unbirthdays in a year.<ref>{{cite book|author=Carroll, Lewis|year=1872|title=Through the looking-glass, and what Alice found there|publisher=Macmillan and Co.|place=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/throughlookinggl01carr#page/122/mode/2up/|pages=121\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nIn the Disney animated film ''Alice in Wonderland'', Alice stumbles upon the [[Hatter (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Mad Hatter]], the [[March Hare]] and the [[Dormouse (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Dormouse]] having an unbirthday party and singing \"The Unbirthday Song\" (music and lyrics by [[Mack David]], [[Al Hoffman]] and [[Jerry Livingston]]). Alice at first doesn't realize what an unbirthday is; when the Mad Hatter explains it to her, she realizes it is ''her'' unbirthday as well, and receives an unbirthday cake from the Mad Hatter. The scene from the film combines the idea of an unbirthday introduced in ''Through the Looking-Glass'' with the \"Mad Tea Party\" described in ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''.<ref>[[Lewis Carroll]] (1865). ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. [[s:Alice's Adventures in Wonderland/Chapter 7|Chapter VII, \"A Mad Tea Party\"]].</ref> Later in the film; the Mad Hatter mentions this unbirthday party when he is summoned as a witness at Alice's trial. The [[King of Hearts (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|King of Hearts]] realizes that it's the [[Queen of Hearts (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Queen of Hearts']] unbirthday as well, and the trial is abruptly halted to celebrate.\n\nThe unbirthday party is also the subject of a 1951 [[Comics|comic]] released to coincide with the film.<ref>[[Walt Disney Productions]] (1951). ''[http://www.nonsenselit.org/comics/walt-disneys-unbirthday-party-with-alice/ Walt Disney's Unbirthday Party with Alice in Wonderland]''. [[Dell Comics|Dell Four Color Comics]] No.&nbsp;341.</ref> The comic version is substantially longer (32&nbsp;pages) than the scene in the animated film, and has Alice being invited to the unbirthday party of [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee]] (who are not actually present at the unbirthday party). Humpty Dumpty is a character in the comic version, although not in the manner in which he appears in ''Through the Looking-Glass''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*''[[s:Through the Looking-Glass|Through the Looking-Glass]]'' at [[Wikisource]]\n\n{{Alice|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Alice in Wonderland]]\n[[Category:Unofficial observances]]\n[[Category:Neologisms]]\n[[Category:Birthdays]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1870s]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Humpty Dumpty Tenniel.jpg|thumb|right|Humpty Dumpty wearing the cravat he received as an unbirthday present from the White King and Queen. From ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'',  illustration by [[John Tenniel]].]]\nAn '''unbirthday''' (originally written '''un-birthday''') is an event that is typically celebrated on any or all of the 364 (365 on leap years) days in which it is not a person's [[birthday]]. It is a [[neologism]] coined by [[Lewis Carroll]] in his 1871 novel ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'',<ref>[[Lewis Carroll]] (1871). ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]''. [[s:Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There/Chapter VI|Chapter VI, \"Humpty Dumpty\"]], written as \"un-birthday\".</ref><ref>''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' [https://archive.org/download/oedxaarch/oedxaarch.pdf vol.&nbsp;10/1] (1926). p.&nbsp;U63 (p.&nbsp;645 of the electronic version).</ref> giving rise to \"The Unbirthday Song\" in the 1951 animated feature film ''[[Alice in Wonderland (1951 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]''.<ref>\"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RdsZT7WKjW8 A Very Merry Unbirthday to You]\". Retrieved on 20 September 2008.<!-- The video is an obvious violation of copyright, but could be used here under the doctrine of fair use--></ref>\n\nOne's unbirthday should not be confused with one's [[half-birthday]], which only occurs once a year.\n\nIn ''Through the Looking-Glass'', [[Humpty Dumpty]] is wearing a [[cravat]] (which [[Alice (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Alice]] at first mistakes for a [[belt (clothing)|belt]]) which he says was given to him as an \"un-birthday present\" by the [[White King (Through the Looking-Glass)|White King]] and [[White Queen (Through the Looking-Glass)|Queen]]. He then has Alice calculate the number of unbirthdays in a year.<ref>{{cite book|author=Carroll, Lewis|year=1872|title=Through the looking-glass, and what Alice found there|publisher=Macmillan and Co.|place=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/throughlookinggl01carr#page/122/mode/2up/|pages=121\u2013123}}</ref>\n\nIn the Disney animated film ''Alice in Wonderland'', Alice stumbles upon the [[Hatter (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Mad Hatter]], the [[March Hare]] and the [[Dormouse (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Dormouse]] having an unbirthday party and singing \"The Unbirthday Song\" (music and lyrics by [[Mack David]], [[Al Hoffman]] and [[Jerry Livingston]]). Alice at first doesn't realize what an unbirthday is; when the Mad Hatter explains it to her, she realizes it is ''her'' unbirthday as well, and receives an unbirthday cake from the Mad Hatter. The scene from the film combines the idea of an unbirthday introduced in ''Through the Looking-Glass'' with the \"Mad Tea Party\" described in ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''.<ref>[[Lewis Carroll]] (1865). ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. [[s:Alice's Adventures in Wonderland/Chapter 7|Chapter VII, \"A Mad Tea Party\"]].</ref> Later in the film; the Mad Hatter mentions this unbirthday party when he is summoned as a witness at Alice's trial. The [[King of Hearts (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|King of Hearts]] realizes that it's the [[Queen of Hearts (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Queen of Hearts']] unbirthday as well, and the trial is abruptly halted to celebrate.\n\nThe unbirthday party is also the subject of a 1951 [[Comics|comic]] released to coincide with the film.<ref>[[Walt Disney Productions]] (1951). ''[http://www.nonsenselit.org/comics/walt-disneys-unbirthday-party-with-alice/ Walt Disney's Unbirthday Party with Alice in Wonderland]''. [[Dell Comics|Dell Four Color Comics]] No.&nbsp;341.</ref> The comic version is substantially longer (32&nbsp;pages) than the scene in the animated film, and has Alice being invited to the unbirthday party of [[Tweedledum and Tweedledee]] (who are not actually present at the unbirthday party). Humpty Dumpty is a character in the comic version, although not in the manner in which he appears in ''Through the Looking-Glass''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*''[[s:Through the Looking-Glass|Through the Looking-Glass]]'' at [[Wikisource]]\n\n{{Alice|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Alice in Wonderland]]\n[[Category:Unofficial observances]]\n[[Category:Neologisms]]\n[[Category:Birthdays]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1870s]]\n", "name_user": "David91x", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u0639\u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f (\u0645\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0628 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0635\u0644 \u0628\u0639\u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f\u0647) \u0647\u0648 \u062d\u062f\u062b \u064a\u062a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062d\u062a\u0641\u0627\u0644 \u0628\u0647 \u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0623\u064a \u0645\u0646 \u0623\u0648 \u0643\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u064a\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0640 364 (365 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0646\u0648\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0628\u064a\u0633\u0629) \u0627\u0644\u062a\u064a \u0644\u0627 \u064a\u0643\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u064a\u0647\u0627 \u0639\u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0634\u062e\u0635.  \u0648\u0647\u064a \u0639\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0639\u0646 \u0646\u064a\u0648\u0644\u0648\u062c\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0635\u0627\u063a\u0647\u0627 \u0644\u0648\u064a\u0633 \u0643\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0644 \u0641\u064a \u0631\u0648\u0627\u064a\u062a\u0647 \u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 1871 \u0645\u0646 \u062e\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0622\u0629 \u060c [1] [2] \u0645\u0645\u0627 \u0623\u062f\u0649 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0638\u0647\u0648\u0631 \"\u0623\u063a\u0646\u064a\u0629 Unbirthday\" \u0641\u064a \u0641\u064a\u0644\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0633\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0645\u064a\u0632 \u0639\u0627\u0645 1951 \u0623\u0644\u064a\u0633 \u0641\u064a \u0628\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062c\u0627\u0626\u0628. [3]   \u0644\u0627 \u064a\u0646\u0628\u063a\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u0637 \u0628\u064a\u0646 \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u0639\u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0621 \u0648\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0646\u0635\u0641 \u0639\u064a\u062f \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f\u0647 \u060c \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a \u064a\u062d\u062f\u062b \u0645\u0631\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f\u0629 \u0641\u0642\u0637 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0646\u0629.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unbirthday"}
{"title_page": "Neal Maupay", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Neal Maupay\n| image = France - England U19, 20150331 11.JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Maupay playing for [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] in 2015\n| fullname = Neal Maupay<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/july-2017.ashx |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/07/2017 and 31/07/2017 |publisher=The Football Association |page=22 |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|8|14|df=y}}<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/16256/Neal-Maupay/overview |title=Neal Maupay: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], France\n| height = 1.73 m<ref name=PremProfile/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]], [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| clubnumber = 7\n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = US Valbonne\n| youthyears2 = 2007\u20132012\n| youthclubs2 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| years1 = 2012\u20132015\n| clubs1 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]]\n| caps1 = 44\n| goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 2012\u20132015\n| clubs2 = [[OGC Nice|Nice II]]\n| caps2 = 13\n| goals2 = 9\n| years3 = 2015\u20132017\n| clubs3 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]]\n| caps3 = 15\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs4 =  [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne II]]\n| caps4 = 6\n| goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 28\n| goals5 = 11\n| years6 = 2017\u20132019\n| clubs6 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps6 = 85\n| goals6 = 37\n| years7 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs7 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| caps7  = 26\n| goals7 = 8\n| nationalyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n| nationalteam1 = [[France national under-16 football team|France U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 13\n| nationalgoals1 = 6\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| nationalteam2 = [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 8\n| nationalgoals2 = 4\n| nationalyears3 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam3 = [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 12\n| nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2014\n| nationalteam4 = [[France national under-21 football team|France U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| club-update = 24 February 2020\n}}\n'''Neal Maupay''' ({{IPA-fr|nil mop\u025b}}; born 14 August 1996) is a French professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|Brigh&HA}} club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. He came to prominence in his homeland with [[OGC Nice|Nice]], [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]] and [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]] and was a [[France national youth football team|France youth international]]. Maupay is also adept as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Nice===\nMaupay began his youth career at US Valbonne at age six in 2002,<ref name=\"getfootballnewsfrance\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.getfootballnewsfrance.com/2013/prospect-neal-maupay/ |title=Prospect: Neal Maupay  {{!}} Get French Football News |website=www.getfootballnewsfrance.com |access-date=15 July 2017}}</ref> before moving into the [[OGC Nice|Nice]] academy in 2007.<ref name=\"sky\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/15198/8502589/Sky-Sports-Scout|title=Sky Sports Scout \u2013 Neal Maupay|date=21 May 2014|website=Sky Sports|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref> He progressed through the ranks into the reserve team at the beginning of the 2012\u201313 season, scoring four goals in three early-season matches before receiving his maiden call into the first team squad on 15 September 2012,<ref name=\"Soccerway\" /> for a [[Ligue 1]] match versus [[Stade Brestois 29|Brest]].<ref name=\"ESPNFC1213\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/178760/neal-maupay?season=2012 |title=Neal Maupay Player Profile \u2013 ESPN FC |website=www.espnfc.com |access-date=15 July 2017}}</ref> At age 16 years and 32 days,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/ofbreves_--p-Nice-Maupay-dans-le-groupe-face-a-Brest-p-_toutes-10371570_filInfosport.Htm |title=Maupay dans le groupe face \u00e0 Brest |date=14 September 2012 |work=Ouest-France |access-date=16 September 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130213122755/http://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/ofbreves_--p-Nice-Maupay-dans-le-groupe-face-a-Brest-p-_toutes-10371570_filInfosport.Htm |archive-date=13 February 2013 |url-status=dead |language=French}}</ref> Maupay made his professional debut as an injury-time substitute for [[\u00c9ric Bauth\u00e9ac]] during the 3\u20132 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice v. Brest Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/75963 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=15 September 2012 |accessdate=16 September 2012 |language = French}}</ref> He was a regular inclusion in the first team squad from October 2012 through to March 2013 and signed a new two-and-a-half year contract in January 2013.<ref name=\"getfootballnewsfrance\" /><ref name=\"ESPNFC1213\" /> Maupay's season was ended by a torn [[cruciate ligament]] suffered during a reserve match on 14 April 2013.<ref name=\"Soccerway\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer-Nice striker Maupay out for rest of the season|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/soccer-france-nice-maupay-idUKL5N0D42I920130417|accessdate=20 August 2016|work=Reuters|date=17 April 2013}}</ref> Maupay made 19 appearances and scored four goals during the [[2012\u201313 Ligue 1|2012\u201313]] season and when making his Ligue 1 debut and scoring his first Ligue 1 goal,<ref name=\"ESPNFC1213\" /> he became the second-youngest player to achieve both feats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2012/m=12/news=predators-prodigy-and-global-glory-1974461.html|title=Predators, a prodigy and global glory|last=FIFA.com|first=|date=19 December 2012|work=FIFA.com|access-date=15 July 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nDespite his breakthrough into the first team squad during the 2012\u201313 season and after recovering from injury, Maupay was out of favour with manager [[Claude Puel]] during [[2013\u201314 Ligue 1|2013\u201314]] and [[2014\u201315 OGC Nice season|2014\u201315]] seasons,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/football/angleterre/football-neal-maupay-j-ai-vraiment-adore-mon-passage-brest-6005278 |title=Football. Neal Maupay\u2009: \"\u2009J\u2019ai vraiment ador\u00e9 mon passage \u00e0 Brest\u2009\" |last=Le Lay |first=Maxime |date=7 October 2018 |website=Ouest-France |language=French |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref> which ultimately caused his departure in August 2015.<ref name=\"ligue1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ligue1.com/ligue1/article/bahebeck-maupay-bolster-sainte-attack.htm |title=Ligue1.com \u2013 Bahebeck, Maupay bolster Saint\u00e9 attack |website=www.ligue1.com |language=en |access-date=15 July 2017}}</ref> He made 53 appearances and scored 9 goals during three seasons as a first team player at the [[Allianz Riviera]].<ref name=\"Soccerway\" />\n\n===Saint-\u00c9tienne===\nOn 10 August 2015, Maupay transferred to Ligue 1 club [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]] on a four-year contract for a \u20ac500,000 fee.<ref name=\"ligue1\" /> Despite making 23 appearances and scoring three goals during the [[2015\u201316 AS Saint-\u00c9tienne season|2015\u201316]] season, he departed on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] for the duration of [[2016\u201317 AS Saint-\u00c9tienne season|2016\u201317]] and left the club in July 2017.<ref name=\"lequipe\" /><ref name=\"brentfordfc\" />\n\n====Brest (loan)====\nOn 20 July 2016, Maupay joined [[Ligue 2]] club Brest on a season-long loan.<ref name=\"lequipe\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Saint-etienne-prete-neal-maupay-a-brest/708307 |title=Saint-Etienne pr\u00eate Neal Maupay \u00e0 Brest |date=20 July 2016 |work=L'Equipe |access-date=20 August 2016 |language=French}}</ref> He had a good start to the [[2016\u201317 Ligue 2|2016\u201317]] season, scoring 10 goals in his opening 21 matches,<ref name=\"ESPNFC1617\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/178760/neal-maupay?season=2016 |title=Neal Maupay Player Profile \u2013 ESPN FC |website=www.espnfc.com |access-date=15 July 2017}}</ref> winning the August 2016 [[UNFP Player of the Month|UNFP Ligue 2 Player of the Month]] award and receiving nominations in September,<ref name=\"UNFP\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.tropheesunfp.com/joueurdumois/nomine-trophee/nomine-trophee-1222/ |title=nomine-trophee 1222 \u2013 Troph\u00e9es UNFP |work=Troph\u00e9es UNFP |access-date=16 July 2017 |language=fr-FR}}</ref> October and December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tropheesunfp.com/joueurdumois/nomine-trophee/nomine-trophee-1677/|title=nomine-trophee 1677 \u2013 Troph\u00e9es UNFP|last=|first=|date=|work=Troph\u00e9es UNFP|access-date=16 July 2017|language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tropheesunfp.com/joueurdumois/nomine-trophee/nomine-trophee-4818/|title=nomine-trophee 4818 \u2013 Troph\u00e9es UNFP|last=|first=|date=|work=Troph\u00e9es UNFP|access-date=16 July 2017|language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tropheesunfp.com/joueurdumois/nomine-trophee/neal-maupay/|title=nomine-trophee 9631 \u2013 Troph\u00e9es UNFP|last=|first=|date=|work=Troph\u00e9es UNFP|access-date=16 July 2017|language=fr-FR}}</ref> Injuries in December 2016 and February 2017 disrupted Maupay's good form and he finished the season with 12 goals in 31 appearances.<ref name=\"Soccerway\" /><ref name=\"ESPNFC1617\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://football.hkjc.com/football/preview/english/2017-03/10/preview-112451.aspx|title=Expert Column \u2013 Preview \u2013 Football \u2013 The Hong Kong Jockey Club|last=|first=|date=|website=football.hkjc.com|access-date=16 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Brentford===\nOn 14 July 2017, Maupay moved to [[Football in England|England]] to join [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on a four-year contract for an undisclosed fee,<ref name=\"brentfordfc\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2017/july/neal-maupay-signs-from-saint-etienne/ |title=Neal Maupay joins from Saint-Etienne |date=14 July 2017 |website=Brentford FC |access-date=14 July 2017}}</ref> reported to be \u00a31.6 million.<ref name=\"brentford1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11748/10949156/brentford-sign-striker-neal-maupay-from-saint-etienne|title=Brentford sign striker Neal Maupay from Saint-Etienne|date=14 July 2017|work=Sky Sports|last1=Thomas|first1=Lyall|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref> The club's France scout Brendan MacFarlane, who would also go on to identify Sa\u00efd Benrahma, Julian Jeanvier and Bryan Mbeumo, played a key role in the identification of the player as a target<ref>https://www.ecofoot.fr/interview-brendan-macfarlane-brentford-3289/</ref>. He was deployed as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] and scored three goals in his opening six appearances for the club,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2017/september/match-report-for-middlesbrough-vs-brentford-on-30-sep-17/|title=Brentford FC Middlesbrough 2 Brentford 2|access-date=21 October 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref> with his first goal coming in a 4\u20133 defeat to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 12 August 2017.<ref name=\"Soccerbase1718\" /> By mid-December, Maupay was considered the best \"[[Substitute (association football)#Super-sub|super-sub]]\" of [[2017\u201318 Brentford F.C. season|2017\u201318]] Championship season so far, with four of his five league goals having been scored during substitute appearances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/brentford-striker-neal-maupay-leading-14023294|title=Neal Maupay is the Championship's top super-sub so far|last=Dubas-Fisher|first=David|date=11 December 2017|work=getwestlondon|access-date=11 December 2017}}</ref> He broke into the starting lineup during the protracted transfer of first choice forward [[Lasse Vibe]] away from [[Griffin Park]] in January 2018 and he assumed the role full time after Vibe's departure early the following month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/178760/neal-maupay?season=2017|title=Neal Maupay Player Profile \u2013 ESPN FC|website=www.espnfc.com|access-date=18 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/february/neal-maupay-post-sunderland/|title=Brentford FC \"It\u2019s been a good day\"|access-date=18 February 2018|language=en-gb}}</ref> Maupay showed improved goalscoring form between mid-January and mid-April, with a run of seven goals in 15 matches.<ref name=\"Soccerbase1718\" /> He finished the 2017\u201318 season with 46 appearances and as the club's top-scorer, with 13 goals.<ref name=\"Soccerbase1718\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?season_id=150&team_id=378&teamTabs=stats&season_id=150|title=Brentford FC Player Appearances {{!}} Past & Present {{!}} Soccer Base|website=www.soccerbase.com|access-date=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nMaupay had an excellent start to the [[2018\u201319 Brentford F.C. season|2018\u201319]] season and scored 13 goals in his first 17 league appearances.<ref name=\"Soccerbase1819\" /> Five goals in August 2018 and four in September led to nominations for the August [[Professional Footballers' Association|PFA]] Fans' Championship Player of the Month and the September [[English Football League|EFL]] Championship [[EFL Championship Player of the Month|Player of the Month]] awards respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2018/9/5/hernandez-wins-augusts-pfa-bristol-street-motors-fans-player-of-the-month|title=Hernandez wins August\u2019s PFA Bristol Street Motors Championship Fans\u2019 Player of the Month|website=www.thepfa.com|language=en|access-date=5 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/october/neal-maupay-beaten-to-sky-bet-championship-player-of-the-month-prize/|title=Neal Maupay beaten to Sky Bet Championship Player of the Month prize|access-date=5 October 2018|language=en-gb}}</ref> 18 goals in 30 appearances by the end of January 2019 saw Maupay win the [[English Football League|EFL]] Player of the Year award at the 2019 London Football Awards.<ref name=\"Soccerbase1819\" /><ref name=\"LFA\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/february/neal-maupay-london-football-award-winner/ |title=Neal Maupay named EFL Player of the Year at London Football Awards |website=www.brentfordfc.com |language=en-gb |accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref> He finished a mid-table season with 28 goals in 49 appearances and was voted the Brentford's Supporters' and Players' [[Brentford F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year]].<ref name=\"Soccerbase1819\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/BRENTFOR.HTM|title=Football Club History Database \u2013 Brentford|website=www.fchd.info|access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"POTY\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2019/may/award-winners-2019/ |title=Maupay takes the honours at Player of the Year Dinner |website=www.brentfordfc.com |language=en-gb |access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nOn 5 August 2019, Maupay moved to [[Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on undisclosed terms,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/august/albion-sign-french-striker/|title=ALBION SIGN FRENCH STRIKER|website=www.brightonandhovealbion.com|date=5 August 2019|access-date=5 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805190019/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/august/albion-sign-french-striker/|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> for a fee reported to be in the region of \u00a320 million on a four-year deal.<ref> {{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48975141|title=Neal Maupay: Brighton sign Brentford forward for reported \u00a320m|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 August 2019}} </ref> Maupay scored on his debut in the opening match of the [[2019\u201320 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2019\u201320]] season, scoring the third for ''The Seagulls'' in a 3\u20130 away win over [[Watford F.C.|Watford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49215983|title=Watford 0\u20133 Brighton: Neal Maupay scores on Seagulls debut - BBC Sport  |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2019|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> On 14 September, Maupay opened the scoreline in a eventual 1\u20131 draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], claiming his first home goal for the Sussex club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617984|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-1 Burnley: Jeff Hendrick scores in stoppage time to earn visitors a point - BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> \n\n==International career==\n[[File:France - England U19, 20150331 12.JPG|thumb|upright|Maupay playing for [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] in 2015]]\n\nMaupay is eligible to play for the [[France national football team|France]] or [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] national teams.<ref name=\"butfootballclub\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.butfootballclub.fr/ligue-1/saint-etienne/asse-exclu-zidane-manchester-united-eysseric-les-confessions-de-maupay/ |title=ASSE \u2013 EXCLU Zidane, Manchester United, Eysseric\u2026 Les confessions de Maupay |work=But! Football Club |access-date=15 July 2017 |language=fr-FR}}</ref> He won 35 caps and scored 16 goals for France at [[France national under-16 football team|U16]], [[France national under-17 football team|U17]], [[France national under-19 football team|U19]] and [[France national under-21 football team|U21]] level.<ref name=\"FFF\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.fff.fr/equipes-de-france/tous-les-joueurs/fiche-joueur/1726241190-neal-maupay |title=Joueur \u2013 Neal MAUPAY \u2013 FFF |work=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise de Football |access-date=15 July 2017 |language=fr}}</ref> He was a member of France's [[2015 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2015 UEFA European U19 Championship]] squad and made two appearances in the tournament.<ref name=\"FFF\" />\n\n==Style of play==\nMaupay's footballing [[Idolatry|idol]] is [[Zinedine Zidane]].<ref name=\"butfootballclub\" /> He stated that he \"can play out [[Winger (association football)|wide]] or as a [[Second striker|number 10]], but my favoured position is striker. I like to play down the middle and use my pace to get in behind defences\" and \"I\u2019m used to looking after the ball and holding off defenders\".<ref name=\"return\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2017/july/neal-maupay-quotes/|title=Brentford FC Neal Maupay ready for Griffin Park return|access-date=15 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaupay was born in [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]] and moved to the [[French Riviera|C\u00f4te d'Azur]] with his family at age five.<ref name=\"getfootballnewsfrance\" /> He is of [[Argentina|Argentinian]] descent on his mother's side.<ref name=\"butfootballclub\" /> He's also ranked 227th in the world at EA SPORTS FIFA 20. \n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|11 January 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Natio