nited Kindgom]]. During the show broadcasting, Ku-Ku Band had its own section called ''Band's Hour'' (''\u0427\u0430\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430'') where the main theme of that show's episode was the band and their members.<ref name=\"tvor\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slavishow.com/\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e-\u043d\u0430-\u043a\u0443-\u043a\u0443-\u0431\u0435\u043d\u0434/|title=\u0422\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u201e\u041a\u0443-\u043a\u0443 \u0431\u0435\u043d\u0434\u201c|publisher=Slavi's Show Official Site|language=Bulgarian}}</ref><ref name=\"slavishow3007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slavishow.com/\u0448\u043e\u0443\u0442\u043e-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438-30-\u044e\u043b\u0438-2019-\u0433/|title=\u0428\u043e\u0443\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438, 30 \u044e\u043b\u0438 2019 \u0433.|publisher=Slavi's Show Official Site|language=Bulgarian}}</ref> Later it started appearing on [[Evening Show of Slavi Trifonov]] (Bulgarian: ''\u0412\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u0422\u0440\u0438\u0444\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432'') on [[7/8 TV]] as successor of the previous show on bTV.<ref name=\"sedemosmi\">{{cite web|url=https://sedemosmi.tv/\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f/\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e-\u0448\u043e\u0443-\u043d\u0430-\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438-\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0444\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432/|title=\u0412\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u0422\u0440\u0438\u0444\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432|publisher=7/8 TV Official Site|language=Bulgarian}}</ref> Till today, the band published 23 albums.<ref name=\"disk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slavishow.com/\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f/|title=\u0414\u0438\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f|publisher=Slavi's Show Official Site|language=Bulgarian}}</ref><ref name=\"78disk\">{{cite web|url=https://sedemosmi.tv/\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f/|title=\u0414\u0438\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f|publisher=7/8 TV Official Site|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n* \"''\u0420\u044a\u0433\u0430\u0439 \u0447\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0431\u0430''\" (''R\u0103gay chushki v boba'', ''\"Poke peppers into bean\"''), 1993\n* \"''\u0428\u0430\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430''\" (''Shat na patkata glavata''), 1994\n* \"''\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430 TV''\" (''Roma TV''), 1994\n* \"''\u0416\u044a\u043b\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043a\u0430''\" (''Zh\u0103lta knizhka'', ''\"Yellow Book\"''), 1995, BMK\n* \"''\u0425\u044a\u0448\u043e\u0432\u0435''\" (''H\u0103shove'', ''\"Outcasts\"''), 1996, BMK\n* \"''\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e The Best''\" (''Kanaleto''), 1997, BMK\n* \"''\u0415\u0434\u043d\u043e \u0444\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0441 \u0446\u0432\u044f\u0442 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0435\u043d''\" (''Edno ferari s cvyat cherven'', ''\"A Red Colored Ferrari\"''), 1997, BMK\n* \"''\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f, \u0437\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0439''\" (''Frantsiya, zdravey'', ''\"Hello France\"''), 1998, BMK\n* \"''\u0414\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d''\" (''Deveti tragichen'', ''\"The Ninth Tragic\"''), 1998, BMK\n* \"''\u0412\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043d''\" (''Vavilon'', \"''Babylon''\"), 1998/99, BMK\n* \"''\u041d\u044f\u043c\u0430 \u201e\u043d\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043c\u201c''\" (''Nyama \"ne iskam\"'', ''\"There's no 'I don't want it'\"''), 1999, BMK\n* \"''\u0427\u0430\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430''\" (''Chas\u0103t na benda'', ''\"The Band's Hour\"''), 2000, BMK\n* \"''\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u0430\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0438''\" (''Novite varvari'', ''\"New Barbarians\"''), 2001, BMK\n* \"''The Best''\", compilation, 2002, BMK\n* \"''Vox populi''\", 2003\n* \"''\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0442''\" (''Prima patriot''), 2004\n* \"''\u0418 \u043e\u0440\u043a\u0435\u0441\u0442\u044a\u0440\u0430 \u0434\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0438''\" (''I orkest\u0103ra da sviri'', ''\"And Orchestra to Play\"''), 2005\n* \"''\u041d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043c\u0435''\" (''Nie prod\u0103lzhavame'', ''\"We continue\"''), 2007\n* \"''No Mercy''\", 2009, Seven-Eight Production\n* \"''\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f''\" (''Makedoniya'', ''\"Macedonia\"''), 2010, Seven-Eight Production\n* \"''\u0415\u0434\u0438\u043d \u043e\u0442 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e''\" (Edin ot mnogoto, \"One of Many\"), 2012\n* \"''\u0418\u043c\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u044a\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434''\" (''Ima tak\u0103v narod'', ''\"There is such a nation\"''), 2017\n* \"''\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438''\" (''Pesni za b\u0103lgari'', ''\"Songs for Bulgarians\"''), 2018\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Slavi Trifonov]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian music]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ku-Ku_Band"}
{"title_page": "Mycoprotein", "text_new": "'''Mycoprotein''' is a form of [[single-cell protein]], also known as '''fungal protein''', that is defined in the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' as \"Protein derived from fungi, especially as produced for human consumption.\" \"Myco\" is from the Greek word for \"[[fungus]]\".\n\n== History ==\nThe only mycoprotein on sale in Europe and North America is called [[Quorn (food product)|Quorn]], created from ''[[Fusarium venenatum]].''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Wiebe|first=M. G.|date=March 2002|title=Myco-protein from Fusarium venenatum: a well-established product for human consumption|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|volume=58|issue=4|pages=421\u2013427|doi=10.1007/s00253-002-0931-x|issn=0175-7598|pmid=11954786}}</ref> In the 1960s ''F. venenatum'' was identified by the English company, [[Rank Hovis McDougall]], as a potential protein source for humans. ''F. venenatum'' was one of more than 3,000 species of fungi screened during a three-year period for being cheap to reproduce, nutritious, and palatable. Concerns for pathogen-potential of the species on plants led to a twelve-year testing process. After this period ''F. venenatum'' was allowed to be sold on the English market and at the time was the most thoroughly tested food product on the European market.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''F. venenatum'' is the only source of mycoprotein that can produce a high percentage of protein biomass approved for market.\n\n== Synthesis ==\nThe fungus is grown in vats using glucose syrup as its food. A fermentation vat is filled with the growth medium and then inoculated with the fungal spores. The ''F. venenatum'' culture [[Cellular respiration|respires]] [[Cellular respiration#Aerobic respiration|aerobically]], so for it to grow at an optimum rate, it is supplied with oxygen, and carbon dioxide is drawn from the vat. To make protein, nitrogen (in the form of [[ammonia]]) is added and vitamins and minerals are needed to support growth. The vat is kept at a constant temperature, also optimized for growth; the fungus can double its mass every five hours.\n\nWhen the desired amount of mycoprotein has been created, the growth medium is drawn off from a tap at the bottom of the fermenter. The mycoprotein is separated and purified. It is a pale yellow solid with a faint taste of mushrooms. Different flavors and tastes can be added to the mycoprotein to add variety.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yoder|first=Wendy T.|last2=Christianson|first2=Lynne M.|date=1998-02-01|title=Species-Specific Primers Resolve Members ofFusariumSectionFusarium: Taxonomic Status of the Edible \"Quorn\" Fungus Reevaluated|journal=Fungal Genetics and Biology|volume=23|issue=1|pages=68\u201380|doi=10.1006/fgbi.1997.1027|pmid=9501478}}</ref>\n\nA reproducible mutation occurs after 1,000 to 1,200 hours of cultivation in F. venenatum that greatly reduces the [[Hypha|hypha length]] in the organism, which is considered unfavorable for production. Under normal conditions, this mutant strain will rapidly displace the parent strain.<ref name=\":0\" /> Replacing ammonia with nitrate as the source of nitrogen, or supplementing ammonium cultures with peptone, prevents this mutant strain from overtaking the product, but will still develop. Alternatively, the appearance of the mutant can be delayed by varying selection pressures such as nutrient concentrations or pH levels.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Health concerns ==\nSome strains of ''F. venenatum'' produce a variety of [[mycotoxin]]s, such as type A [[Trichothecene|tichothecenes]]. Mycotoxin-producing genes such as isotrichodermin, isotricodermol, sambucinol, apo-trichothecen, culmorin, culmorone, and enniatin B can be found in cultures of ''F. venenatum''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Specific strands that do not produce mycotoxins under optimal conditions can be selected to reduce the danger to human consumers. Testing at six-hour intervals can be done to monitor mycotoxin presence.\n\nThere is continual testing for concerns of allergic reactions, which can range from abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting to severe asthmatic reactions,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hoff|first=Michael|last2=Tr\u00fceb|first2=Ralph M.|last3=Ballmer-Weber|first3=Barbara K.|last4=Vieths|first4=Stefan|last5=Wuethrich|first5=Brunello|date=2003-05-01|title=Immediate-type hypersensitivity reaction to ingestion of mycoprotein (Quorn) in a patient allergic to molds caused by acidic ribosomal protein P2|url=http://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(03)80140-9/abstract|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|language=English|volume=111|issue=5|pages=1106\u20131110|doi=10.1067/mai.2003.1339|issn=0091-6749|pmid=12743577}}</ref> especially when crossed with inhaled [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] spores.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Durme|first=Paul Van|last2=Ceuppens|first2=Jan L.|last3=Cadot|first3=Pascal|date=2003-08-01|title=Allergy to ingested mycoprotein in a patient with mold spore inhalant allergy|url=http://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(03)90001-7/abstract|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|language=English|volume=112|issue=2|pages=452\u2013454|doi=10.1067/mai.2003.1613|issn=0091-6749|pmid=12897757}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition potential ==\nMycoprotein is able to provide greater satiety than traditional protein sources such as chicken, while also being rich in protein and low in caloric content. Replacing two servings of meat protein with mycoprotein can result in a daily deficit of {{convert|80|kcal|kJ}},<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Williamson|first=Donald A.|last2=Geiselman|first2=Paula J.|last3=Lovejoy|first3=Jennifer|last4=Greenway|first4=Frank|last5=Volaufova|first5=Julia|last6=Martin|first6=Corby K.|last7=Arnett|first7=Cheryl|last8=Ortego|first8=Lauren|date=January 2006|title=Effects of consuming mycoprotein, tofu or chicken upon subsequent eating behaviour, hunger and safety|journal=Appetite|volume=46|issue=1|pages=41\u201348|doi=10.1016/j.appet.2005.10.007|issn=0195-6663|pmid=16364496}}</ref> whilst also extending the period of satiation, which is promising for weight management programs. Mycoprotein is rich in fiber and protein content, but very low in fat, making it a desirable food source for consumers trying to limit fat intake while still participating in a high protein diet.\n\n''F. venenatum''<nowiki/>'s high fiber content also has potential in managing blood sugar levels. The mechanism that links fiber content and F. venenatum's effect on managing glycemia and insulenaemia is not completely understood, but it is known to decrease the rate of glucose absorption and insulin secretion and it helps mitigate the maximum limit an amount of insulin can process glucose, known as insulin peak.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=A.|last2=Aisbitt|first2=B.|last3=Lunn|first3=J.|date=2008-12-01|title=Mycoprotein and health|url=https://insights.ovid.com/nutrition-bulletin/nutbu/2008/12/000/mycoprotein-health/5/00094955|journal=Nutrition Bulletin|language=ENGLISH|volume=33|issue=4|issn=1471-9827}}</ref>\n\nUnder optimum conditions ''F. venenatum'' biomass can be 42% protein while also functioning as a [[Prebiotic (nutrition)|prebiotic]] material for the lower gut.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Fusarium venenatum]]''\n* [[Fungiculture]]\n* [[Quorn]]\n* [[Protein quality]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal| first1 = M.G.| last1 =  Wiebe| title = Myco-protein from Fusarium venenatum: a well-established product for human consumption| journal = Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology| volume = 58| pages = 421\u20137| doi = 10.1007/s00253-002-0931-x| issue = 4| year = 2002| pmid = 11954786}}\n\n[[Category:Fungal proteins]]\n[[Category:Meat substitutes]]\n[[Category:Single-cell protein]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mycoprotein''' is a form of [[single-cell protein]], also known as '''fungal protein''', that is defined in the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' as \"Protein derived from fungi, especially as produced for human consumption.\" \"Myco\" is from the Greek word for \"[[fungus]]\".\n\n== History ==\nThe only mycoprotein on sale in Europe and North America is called [[Quorn (food product)|Quorn]], created from ''[[Fusarium venenatum]].''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Wiebe|first=M. G.|date=March 2002|title=Myco-protein from Fusarium venenatum: a well-established product for human consumption|journal=Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology|volume=58|issue=4|pages=421\u2013427|doi=10.1007/s00253-002-0931-x|issn=0175-7598|pmid=11954786}}</ref> In the 1960s ''F. venenatum'' was identified by the English company, [[Rank Hovis McDougall]], as a potential protein source for humans. ''F. venenatum'' was one of more than 3,000 species of fungi screened during a three-year period for being cheap to reproduce, nutritious, and palatable. Concerns for pathogen-potential of the species on plants led to a twelve-year testing process. After this period ''F. venenatum'' was allowed to be sold on the English market and at the time was the most thoroughly tested food product on the European market.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''F. venenatum'' is the only source of mycoprotein that can produce a high percentage of protein biomass approved for market.\n\n== Synthesis ==\nThe fungus is grown in vats using glucose syrup as its food. A fermentation vat is filled with the growth medium and then inoculated with the fungal spores. The ''F. venenatum'' culture [[Cellular respiration|respires]] [[Cellular respiration#Aerobic respiration|aerobically]], so for it to grow at an optimum rate, it is supplied with oxygen, and carbon dioxide is drawn from the vat. To make protein, nitrogen (in the form of [[ammonia]]) is added and vitamins and minerals are needed to support growth. The vat is kept at a constant temperature, also optimized for growth; the fungus can double its mass every five hours.\n\nWhen the desired amount of mycoprotein has been created, the growth medium is drawn off from a tap at the bottom of the fermenter. The mycoprotein is separated and purified. It is a pale yellow solid with a faint taste of mushrooms. Different flavors and tastes can be added to the mycoprotein to add variety.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yoder|first=Wendy T.|last2=Christianson|first2=Lynne M.|date=1998-02-01|title=Species-Specific Primers Resolve Members ofFusariumSectionFusarium: Taxonomic Status of the Edible \"Quorn\" Fungus Reevaluated|journal=Fungal Genetics and Biology|volume=23|issue=1|pages=68\u201380|doi=10.1006/fgbi.1997.1027|pmid=9501478}}</ref>\n\nA reproducible mutation occurs after 1,000 to 1,200 hours of cultivation in F. venenatum that greatly reduces the [[Hypha|hypha length]] in the organism, which is considered unfavorable for production. Under normal conditions, this mutant strain will rapidly displace the parent strain.<ref name=\":0\" /> Replacing ammonia with nitrate as the source of nitrogen, or supplementing ammonium cultures with peptone, prevents this mutant strain from overtaking the product, but will still develop. Alternatively, the appearance of the mutant can be delayed by varying selection pressures such as nutrient concentrations or pH levels.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Health concerns ==\nSome strains of ''F. venenatum'' produce a variety of [[mycotoxin]]s, such as type A [[Trichothecene|tichothecenes]]. Mycotoxin-producing genes such as isotrichodermin, isotricodermol, sambucinol, apo-trichothecen, culmorin, culmorone, and enniatin B can be found in cultures of ''F. venenatum''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Specific strands that do not produce mycotoxins under optimal conditions can be selected to reduce the danger to human consumers. Testing at six-hour intervals can be done to monitor mycotoxin presence.\n\nThere is continual testing for concerns of allergic reactions, which can range from abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting to severe asthmatic reactions,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hoff|first=Michael|last2=Tr\u00fceb|first2=Ralph M.|last3=Ballmer-Weber|first3=Barbara K.|last4=Vieths|first4=Stefan|last5=Wuethrich|first5=Brunello|date=2003-05-01|title=Immediate-type hypersensitivity reaction to ingestion of mycoprotein (Quorn) in a patient allergic to molds caused by acidic ribosomal protein P2|url=http://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(03)80140-9/abstract|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|language=English|volume=111|issue=5|pages=1106\u20131110|doi=10.1067/mai.2003.1339|issn=0091-6749|pmid=12743577}}</ref> especially when crossed with inhaled mold spores.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Durme|first=Paul Van|last2=Ceuppens|first2=Jan L.|last3=Cadot|first3=Pascal|date=2003-08-01|title=Allergy to ingested mycoprotein in a patient with mold spore inhalant allergy|url=http://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(03)90001-7/abstract|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|language=English|volume=112|issue=2|pages=452\u2013454|doi=10.1067/mai.2003.1613|issn=0091-6749|pmid=12897757}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition potential ==\nMycoprotein is able to provide greater satiety than traditional protein sources such as chicken, while also being rich in protein and low in caloric content. Replacing two servings of meat protein with mycoprotein can result in a daily deficit of {{convert|80|kcal|kJ}},<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Williamson|first=Donald A.|last2=Geiselman|first2=Paula J.|last3=Lovejoy|first3=Jennifer|last4=Greenway|first4=Frank|last5=Volaufova|first5=Julia|last6=Martin|first6=Corby K.|last7=Arnett|first7=Cheryl|last8=Ortego|first8=Lauren|date=January 2006|title=Effects of consuming mycoprotein, tofu or chicken upon subsequent eating behaviour, hunger and safety|journal=Appetite|volume=46|issue=1|pages=41\u201348|doi=10.1016/j.appet.2005.10.007|issn=0195-6663|pmid=16364496}}</ref> whilst also extending the period of satiation, which is promising for weight management programs. Mycoprotein is rich in fiber and protein content, but very low in fat, making it a desirable food source for consumers trying to limit fat intake while still participating in a high protein diet.\n\n''F. venenatum''<nowiki/>'s high fiber content also has potential in managing blood sugar levels. The mechanism that links fiber content and F. venenatum's effect on managing glycemia and insulenaemia is not completely understood, but it is known to decrease the rate of glucose absorption and insulin secretion and it helps mitigate the maximum limit an amount of insulin can process glucose, known as insulin peak.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Denny|first=A.|last2=Aisbitt|first2=B.|last3=Lunn|first3=J.|date=2008-12-01|title=Mycoprotein and health|url=https://insights.ovid.com/nutrition-bulletin/nutbu/2008/12/000/mycoprotein-health/5/00094955|journal=Nutrition Bulletin|language=ENGLISH|volume=33|issue=4|issn=1471-9827}}</ref>\n\nUnder optimum conditions ''F. venenatum'' biomass can be 42% protein while also functioning as a [[Prebiotic (nutrition)|prebiotic]] material for the lower gut.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Fusarium venenatum]]''\n* [[Fungiculture]]\n* [[Mold|Filamentous fungi]]\n* [[Quorn]]\n* [[Protein quality]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal| first1 = M.G.| last1 =  Wiebe| title = Myco-protein from Fusarium venenatum: a well-established product for human consumption| journal = Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology| volume = 58| pages = 421\u20137| doi = 10.1007/s00253-002-0931-x| issue = 4| year = 2002| pmid = 11954786}}\n\n[[Category:Fungal proteins]]\n[[Category:Meat substitutes]]\n[[Category:Single-cell protein]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "link mold in text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycoprotein"}
